passages.text: CW | AFL | Siemens (Phil Buller/David Adlington/Benjamin Defay) (SIE GR, OW, PT €300.00), Germany

With the decade- long conglomerate discount versus peers now all but gone, buying Siemens at this point necessitates confidence that the company can sustainably outgrow earnings and/or warrant a premium valuation versus peers. Our analysis suggests both are probable. In this cross- asset and cross- sector note, we explore the prospects for the Siemens AG (SIE) and Siemens Healthineers AG (SHL) equities under different simplification scenarios ahead of an important December 9 CMD, in addition to assessing the impact this would have on credit metrics. We are moving to an OW (from NR) with a Dec- 26 PT of €300 (c30% upside), place the stock on Positive Catalyst Watch into the CMD and add it to our Analyst Focus List.
Novonesis (Chetan Udeshi, CFA) (NSISB DC, OW, PT Dkr512.00), Denmark

The organic sales growth (OSG) CAGR target of \(6 - 9\%\) from 2025 to 2030 that Novonesis (NSISB) management presented last week remains best in class in our coverage. We are encouraged by the breadth of growth opportunities across multiple end markets, as is also reflected in at least HSD's OSG seen across all the key divisions in 1H25. The key mantra remains to stretch the core by leveraging its enviable technological edge (9%+ R&D/sales) and its ability to customize offerings (which also drives higher differentiation and pricing power) to increase penetration of its existing and new products, while also exploring growth from potential new applications/markets. This also partly explains the higher than expected capex/sales guidance of LDD% for the next three years (vs. our previous estimate of \(\sim 10\%\) ) as the company is building a platform to be able to deliver faster growth (up to \(9\%\) CAGR) than seen in the past ( \(\sim 6\%\) OSG CAGR over the past 10 years) with an underlying post- tax ROIC of \(>20\%\) . We cut our FY25- 28E adj EPS by \(4 - 5\%\) , largely to reflect the incremental FX headwinds and as a result we also trim our Dec 2026 PT to DKK 512 (DKK 545). That said, with a potential \(10\% +\) adj EPS CAGR over the next 3- 5 years with high underlying ROIC, we see the recent derating - FY25/26/27E P/E of 28x/26x/24x vs. the historical long- term multiple of \(\sim 30x\) - as an attractive entry point, with our DCF model suggesting an upside potential to DKK 590. Remain OW.
AFL | EU Oil & Gas: Taking Stock (Matthew Lofting, CFA), Europe

Ahead of Autumn conference season including J.P. Morgan's EU Oils 'Back to School' seminar, hosted virtually 29 August – 8 September, we take stock on key sector metrics and provide a renewed EU Majors Question Bank of pertinent issues to discuss in management meetings. Topics are organized under industrial and fiscal subheadings and presented alongside each corporate's summary financials.
Meituan (3690) (Alex Yao) (3690 HK, OW, PT HK\$150.00), China

Meituan turned out to have invested Rmb10bn more in food delivery and quick commerce in 2Q25 than we previously expected, indicating that irrational competition is likely much more intense than market expectations. We expect consensus estimates to be revised down post the print to factor in 2Q numbers and likely greater investments in 3Q. We expect the share price to react negatively to the print.

KSOE announced the merger of HD Hyundai Heavy Industries (HHI) and HD Hyundai Mipo (Mipo) today. This move clearly shows the group's change in business structure from commercial- centric to higher exposure to the navy business, and the company will utilize its key assets under Mipo and overseas subsidiaries (i.e., HD HVS, HD HHIP and HD Hyundai Vina + a potential US subsidiary potentially established under KSOE). We are positive on this move, as we believe a re- rating for Korean shipbuilders should come mostly from the defense angle. Our key takeaways from today's announcement are: (1) the company's high conviction in navy demand not just for the US, but also for the rest of the world; (2) agile capacity expansion and utilization of commercial docks to help grow navy- related revenue from W1T in 2025 to W10T by 2035; and (3) the company's confidence in profitability, given its unmatched cost- competitiveness. While there are some concerns about the setting up of the Singapore Investment Corp entity that would govern the ASEAN subsidiaries, we think this structure will help to fully capitalize and centralize assets that were previously dispersed under different companies. We reiterate our OW on HHI, KSOE and Mipo, along with Hanwha Ocean, as we expect to see valuation unlock for their global navy market exposure. Keys to watch from here are: (1) order visibility for the US and global navy business; (2) an update on US regulatory changes to allow Koreans to build outside the US; and (3) details on Korea's \(\) 150B\$ commitment into the US.
Futu Holdings (Katherine Lei/Peter Zhang) (FUTU, OW, PT \$270.00), China

We raised Futu's EPS forecasts post a strong 2Q25 print (link), and in this note, we increase the valuation multiple and raise our PT by \(35\%\) to US\$270, implying 28x 2026E PE. The key drivers for this re- rating are as follows: First, there is a strong correlation between the growth outlook and PE multiple. Futu has demonstrated significant growth in clients, AUM, revenue, and profits since 2024, yet the multiple re- rating has lagged (current 26E PE of 20x vs historical FY1 mean of 23x). Second, we believe strong client acquisition in HK/SG/MY, rise in wallet share per client and digital assets development will further drive growth momentum. Third, Futu is trading at a steep discount to peers (Hood, IBKR & EM), despite a better growth outlook. With an easing of the regulatory overhang, we expect the discount to narrow. We remain OW.
Personal Care Sector (Japan) (Akiko Kuwahara), Japan

The 2Q- FY2025 results confirmed that domestic earnings are improving at the personal care companies under our coverage. Over time near term, there appears to be good visibility on the improvement in domestic earnings at each company. In contrast, market fluctuations are having an increasingly negative impact on overseas operations, and this is weighing on share price upside. We reiterate our Overweight rating on Lion (4912), which is making flexible changes to its overseas strategy and is starting to see contributions from its domestic strategy as well. For Kao (4452, Overweight), we raise our price target from \(7,600 to\) 7,700 in anticipation of improved sales trends in the overseas cosmetics business from 2H FY2025. We also take a positive view of the share buyback announced by the company. For Unicharm (8113, Overweight), we lower our price target from \(1,350 to\) 1,250 but view 2Q as generally the bottom for earnings. From a medium- to long- term perspective, we see considerable room for a rebound in its share price.
MENA Food Retail (Elena Jouronova, CFA), Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates
LFLs subdued, opex on the rise, expansion plans- assessed - we cut forecasts and PTs across our Saudi coverage

We maintain our cautious stance on the Saudi food retail sector, as uninspiring revenue and earnings delivery in 2Q25 results have reinforced our concerns and prompted us to cut forecasts and PTs across our Saudi coverage. The growth of the online and discounter channels, acknowledged as a threat by Othaim during the 2Q25 results call, is prompting a reevaluation of store growth strategies among offline retailers while rising personnel and lease costs dampen profitability prospects. We continue to favor Spinneys in the MENA food retail space given its exposure to the UAE, where market dynamics are more favorable and where we see business model differentiation and strong competitive moat; its expansion into Kuwait presents additional upside potential. We continue to find valuations elevated for Alothaim & BinDawood (18- 22 P/Es for JPME 3- 7% EPS CAGR in 2025- 27E) and believe that Spinneys offers a better risk- reward.

We are updating our estimates for Brazilian Malls (MULT, IGTI and ALOS) and establishing our Dec- 26 PT, which are on average \(15\%\) above our previous targets. We continue to flag that the sector's performance remains highly correlated to real rates; therefore our OW is supported by JPM's bullish view on rates for 2026YE at \(10.75\%\) vs consensus at \(\sim 13.9\%\) , with cuts already starting this year. On the bottom- up front, our positive view is justified by: i) Attractive upside of \(33 - 34\%\) to our Dec- 26 PTs; ii) Spread of 310bps to long- term real rates vs historical levels of \(\sim 180\) bps (10Y); and iii) Tailwinds from non- core operations such as land plot sales, real estate development and media results. We are making small changes to our estimates, increasing FFO per share by \(6 - 9\%\) for 2026 reflecting mostly higher than expected top- line. We maintain our relative preference of MULT > IGTI > ALOS. We favor low- income homebuilders vs. malls as 2H25 should be relatively stronger as the sector counts on continuous support from the MCMV program, while Malls' results should be impacted by softer IGPM.
Woolworths Group Ltd (Bryan Raymond) (WOW AU, N, PT A\(29.60), Australia

Woolworths' eight- week trading update and FY26 earnings outlook was well below consensus expectations. We downgrade our FY26 Australian Food EBIT growth outlook from \(+4.1\%\) YoY to \(+2.3\%\) YoY, as we expect Woolworths will find it challenging to meet guidance, given sales underperformance, wage costs, system investment, price investment and theft headwinds. We expect Food EBIT margin to contract by - 6bps YoY to \(5.3\%\) , and stand 26bps below Coles, the first time Coles will have a higher supermarket EBIT margin than Woolworths in 10 years. Food downgrades, in addition to BIG W and corporate cost downgrades drive EPS downgrades of \(- 7.2\%\) in FY26 and \(- 4.6\%\) in FY27. We maintain our Neutral rating with an Aug- 26 price target of A\(29.60 (- 5\%\) from \(31.00 prior).
